 {"id":"bd-36l.1","title":"Implement differentiated exit codes for --check-drift (0=OK, 1=critical, 2=warning)","description":"Go's --check-drift returns exit code 0 when no drift detected, 1 when critical drift found, 2 when only warnings. Rust's --robot-drift (robot_drift flag in cli.rs:306) runs drift analysis but doesn't use differentiated exit codes — it always exits 0 on success. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) In src/main.rs where robot_drift is handled, after computing drift results, check severity. (2) If any critical-severity drifts found, return ExitCode::from(1). (3) If only warning-severity, return ExitCode::from(2). (4) If clean, return ExitCode::SUCCESS. (5) Document exit codes in --robot-docs output. Go ref: main.go line 125 comment. ACCEPTANCE: Test that critical drift produces exit 1, warning-only produces exit 2, clean produces exit 0.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:48.696608855Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T00:39:16.138276363Z","closed_at":"2026-03-08T00:39:16.137891422Z","close_reason":"Already implemented in analysis/drift.rs:381-387. compute_drift() returns exit_code: 1 for critical, 2 for warning, 0 for OK. Tests verify this at drift.rs:583 and drift.rs:600. No work needed.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.1","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:48.696608855Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":21,"issue_id":"bd-36l.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: cmd/bv/main.go checkDrift() — returns exit code 0 for OK, 1 for critical drift detected, 2 for warnings only. Our Rust --check-drift always returns 0 or 1. Scripts use exit codes to gate CI/CD pipelines, so the three-level scheme is important.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:12Z"},{"id":76,"issue_id":"bd-36l.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:16Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-36l.2","title":"Support BV_OUTPUT_FORMAT env var for json/toon format selection","description":"Go respects BV_PRETTY_JSON=1 to pretty-print robot JSON output (with indentation). Rust's robot.rs line 166 references encode_json() but may not check this env var. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) In src/robot.rs encode_json(), check std::env::var('BV_PRETTY_JSON'). (2) If set to '1', use serde_json::to_string_pretty() instead of to_string(). (3) This should already be partially implemented — verify and add test. Go ref: main.go line 7485. ACCEPTANCE: BV_PRETTY_JSON=1 bvr --robot-triage produces indented JSON.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:49.948466834Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T00:38:40.308254127Z","closed_at":"2026-03-08T00:38:40.307537856Z","close_reason":"Already implemented in cli.rs:475-483. resolve_output_format() checks BV_OUTPUT_FORMAT and TOON_DEFAULT_FORMAT env vars with full test coverage (cli.rs:677-703). No work needed.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.2","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:49.948466834Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":22,"issue_id":"bd-36l.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: cmd/bv/main.go — checks BV_PRETTY_JSON env var to output indented JSON. Our Rust robot output is always compact. This is a one-liner (serde_json::to_string_pretty when env var is set) but matters for debugging and manual inspection.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:13Z"},{"id":51,"issue_id":"bd-36l.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"CORRECTION: Previous description referenced BV_PRETTY_JSON which does NOT exist in Go. Go actually uses --format json|toon CLI flag with env var fallbacks BV_OUTPUT_FORMAT and TOON_DEFAULT_FORMAT. The Rust port already has --format support but may not check the env vars. Fix: ensure BV_OUTPUT_FORMAT and TOON_DEFAULT_FORMAT env vars are checked as fallback when --format is not specified, matching Go's resolveRobotOutputFormat() logic (cmd/bv/main.go lines 7502-7512).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:32:44Z"},{"id":77,"issue_id":"bd-36l.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:16Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-36l.3","title":"Split --related-limit into --related-min-relevance and --related-max-results","description":"Go has two separate flags for related-work filtering: --related-min-relevance (int, default 20, minimum relevance score threshold) and --related-max-results (int, default 10, max results per category). Rust collapsed both into a single --related-limit flag (cli.rs:287). IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Replace related_limit in Cli struct with related_min_relevance: Option<u32> (default 20) and related_max_results: Option<u32> (default 10). (2) Update all call sites that use related_limit to use the appropriate new flag. (3) Keep --related-limit as a deprecated alias that sets both. Go ref: main.go lines 155-156. ACCEPTANCE: Both flags work independently. Legacy --related-limit still works.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:51.022077564Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T03:58:46.300950905Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T03:58:46.300541208Z","close_reason":"Split --related-limit into --related-min-relevance (default 20, minimum relevance threshold) and --related-max-results (default 10, max results). find_related_work() now filters by min_relevance before truncating to max_results. 474 lib tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.3","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:51.022077564Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":23,"issue_id":"bd-36l.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: cmd/bv/main.go — separate --related-min-relevance (float threshold) and --related-max-results (integer cap). Our Rust has single --related-limit that conflates count and relevance. Splitting them gives users finer control over related-issue output.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:17Z"},{"id":78,"issue_id":"bd-36l.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:17Z"}]}
-{"id":"bd-36l.4","title":"Convert Issue timestamp fields from String to DateTime<Utc> for type consistency","description":"Rust's Issue struct stores created_at, updated_at, due_date, closed_at as Option<String> while Sprint stores start_date, end_date as Option<DateTime<Utc>>. This inconsistency means timestamp comparisons in analysis code require repeated parsing. Go uses time.Time for all timestamp fields. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Change created_at, updated_at, due_date, closed_at in src/model.rs from Option<String> to Option<DateTime<Utc>> using chrono. (2) Use #[serde(deserialize_with)] for flexible parsing (ISO8601/RFC3339). (3) Update all code that accesses these fields — grep for '.created_at', '.updated_at', '.due_date', '.closed_at' across src/. (4) Update serialization to maintain RFC3339 string output. (5) Comment.created_at should also be converted. WARNING: This is a wide-reaching change touching model.rs, triage.rs, diff.rs, suggest.rs, history.rs, robot.rs, main.rs, tui.rs. Thorough testing required. ACCEPTANCE: All timestamp fields are DateTime<Utc>. All 627+ tests still pass. JSON output unchanged.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:52.141817913Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:17.624165184Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.4","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:52.141817913Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":24,"issue_id":"bd-36l.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"REFACTOR: Currently Issue struct uses String for created_at, updated_at, closed_at. Go uses time.Time. String comparison breaks sorting by date, makes duration calculations fragile, and requires parse-on-use throughout the codebase. Convert to chrono::DateTime<Utc> with serde support. This touches model.rs, loader.rs, and any code that reads/writes these fields. Test carefully — date parsing edge cases (missing timezone, epoch 0, future dates) must all work. BLOCKS bd-3dh.12 (time-travel needs real timestamps).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:23Z"},{"id":79,"issue_id":"bd-36l.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:17Z"}]}
+{"id":"bd-36l.4","title":"Convert Issue timestamp fields from String to DateTime<Utc> for type consistency","description":"Rust's Issue struct stores created_at, updated_at, due_date, closed_at as Option<String> while Sprint stores start_date, end_date as Option<DateTime<Utc>>. This inconsistency means timestamp comparisons in analysis code require repeated parsing. Go uses time.Time for all timestamp fields. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Change created_at, updated_at, due_date, closed_at in src/model.rs from Option<String> to Option<DateTime<Utc>> using chrono. (2) Use #[serde(deserialize_with)] for flexible parsing (ISO8601/RFC3339). (3) Update all code that accesses these fields — grep for '.created_at', '.updated_at', '.due_date', '.closed_at' across src/. (4) Update serialization to maintain RFC3339 string output. (5) Comment.created_at should also be converted. WARNING: This is a wide-reaching change touching model.rs, triage.rs, diff.rs, suggest.rs, history.rs, robot.rs, main.rs, tui.rs. Thorough testing required. ACCEPTANCE: All timestamp fields are DateTime<Utc>. All 627+ tests still pass. JSON output unchanged.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:52.141817913Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T06:36:39.815905301Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.4","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:52.141817913Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":24,"issue_id":"bd-36l.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"REFACTOR: Currently Issue struct uses String for created_at, updated_at, closed_at. Go uses time.Time. String comparison breaks sorting by date, makes duration calculations fragile, and requires parse-on-use throughout the codebase. Convert to chrono::DateTime<Utc> with serde support. This touches model.rs, loader.rs, and any code that reads/writes these fields. Test carefully — date parsing edge cases (missing timezone, epoch 0, future dates) must all work. BLOCKS bd-3dh.12 (time-travel needs real timestamps).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:23Z"},{"id":79,"issue_id":"bd-36l.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:17Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-36l.5","title":"Separate is_closed() from is_tombstone() in status semantics","description":"Go distinguishes IsClosed() (only 'closed') from IsTombstone() (only 'tombstone'), while Rust's is_closed_like() treats BOTH as closed. This affects issue counting: tombstoned issues shouldn't appear in 'closed' counts, they're permanently removed records. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) In src/model.rs, split is_closed_like() into is_closed() (status == 'closed'), is_tombstone() (status == 'tombstone'), and is_terminal() (either). (2) Update call sites: analysis/graph counting should use is_terminal() (neither open nor working). Triage counts should distinguish. Robot output counts (open/closed/tombstone) should be separate. (3) Keep is_open_like() as \\!is_terminal() for backward compat. Go ref: pkg/model/types.go Status.IsClosed(), Status.IsTombstone(). ACCEPTANCE: is_closed() returns false for tombstone. Separate counts in triage output.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:53.347363059Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T03:49:48.435730353Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T03:49:48.434833193Z","close_reason":"Added is_closed() and is_tombstone() methods to Issue model. is_closed_like() retained as terminal status check. SnapshotCounts in diff.rs now tracks tombstone separately with terminal() accessor. 1 new unit test. 474 lib tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:53.347363059Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":25,"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/model/issue.go — is_closed() means work is done. is_tombstone() means the issue was deleted/merged/superseded. Currently Rust treats both the same (any non-open status). The distinction matters for metrics — tombstoned issues shouldn't count in velocity calculations but closed ones should.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:27Z"},{"id":80,"issue_id":"bd-36l.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:17Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-36l.6","title":"Add missing model fields: content_hash, external_ref","description":"Go Issue struct has content_hash (string, json:\"-\" — internal use for dedup), external_ref (*string, omitempty — link to external tracker), compaction_level/compacted_at/compacted_at_commit/original_size (compaction metadata). Of these, content_hash and external_ref are most impactful. Compaction fields are less critical (they're for the beads CLI sync optimization). IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Add content_hash: Option<String> with #[serde(default, skip_serializing)] to Issue in model.rs (computed, not serialized). (2) Add external_ref: Option<String> with serde(default, skip_serializing_if='Option::is_none') to Issue. (3) Compute content_hash during loading if needed (SHA256 of id+title+description+status). (4) Low priority: compaction fields can be deferred or excluded. ACCEPTANCE: external_ref round-trips through JSONL. content_hash available internally for dedup logic.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:54.819141972Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T04:07:48.408254084Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T04:07:48.407813889Z","close_reason":"Added content_hash (skip_serializing, internal dedup) and external_ref (optional, skip_serializing_if None) to Issue model. external_ref shown in TUI detail pane when present. Updated 2 test helpers with explicit fields. 1 new unit test. 475 lib tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","depends_on_id":"bd-36l","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:57:54.819141972Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":26,"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/model/issue.go — content_hash (SHA-256 of issue body, used for change detection) and external_ref (link to GitHub/Jira/Linear issue). Both are optional fields. content_hash enables efficient diff detection. external_ref enables cross-system linking.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:07:29Z"},{"id":59,"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"IMPORTANT DETAIL: In Go, ContentHash has json:\"-\" tag (NOT exported to JSON). It's used internally for change detection, not in API output. ExternalRef is json:\"external_ref,omitempty\" (pointer type, optional). Implementation: content_hash should be computed on load and stored in Issue struct but excluded from serde serialization (#[serde(skip)]). external_ref should be Option<String> with #[serde(skip_serializing_if = \"Option::is_none\")].","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:33:58Z"},{"id":81,"issue_id":"bd-36l.6","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes tests using assert_cmd for CLI behavior verification. Test both the happy path and error cases. For env var tests, use std::env::set_var in a serial test (not parallel).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:18Z"}]}
